TY  - JOUR
AU  - Schwarz, Krista
T1  - Mind the Gap: Disentangling Credit and Liquidity in Risk Spreads*
PY  - 2019
Y1  - 2019/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfy034
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 23
IS  - 3
SP  - 557
EP  - 597
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - Euro-area sovereign bond and interbank interest rate spreads spiked in the 2007–2009 Global Financial Crisis and the subsequent European Debt Crisis, substantially elevating financing costs. I use a model-free measure of market liquidity to precisely identify the relative contribution of credit versus liquidity to spreads in these episodes. In the Financial Crisis, liquidity is paramount, accounting for 36% of trough-to-peak widening, after controlling for credit. However, default risk becomes relatively more important to sovereign spreads in the Debt Crisis. Aggregate bond liquidity explains a substantial portion of interbank spreads throughout the sample.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfy034
ER  - 



